{"id":"holomush-phq3.20","title":"No unit test for MoveHandler ErrAccessEvaluationFailed path propagation from GetExitsByLocation","description":"move.go adds three ErrAccessEvaluationFailed preservation branches (lines 7310-7312, 7321-7323, 7332-7334). The PR adds move_test.go tests for all three branches: TestMoveHandler_AccessEvaluationFailureOnGetExits, TestMoveHandler_AccessEvaluationFailureOnMoveCharacter, and TestMoveHandler_AccessEvaluationFailureOnGetLocationAfterMove.

However, TestMoveHandler_AccessEvaluationFailureOnGetExits at line 7602 checks for code 'EXIT_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED' but GetExitsByLocation uses entity prefix 'EXIT' for the location read check (resource=location:<id>, entityPrefix='EXIT') — so the code produced is EXIT_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED even though the failure is on reading the location that contains the exits. This is correct per the implementation, but the test comment says 'Get exits from current location' while the actual operation failing is the location read. The test is valid, but documenting this non-obvious naming would prevent future confusion.

This is a suggestion (test documentation quality) rather than a coverage gap.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:10:47Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:10:47Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.25","title":"hasBypass doc comment contradicts implementation — claims errors not propagated but code propagates them","description":"File: internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go

The inline comment on the engine.Evaluate() error path (lines added in PR) reads:

  // Design decision: engine errors in bypass check return false (no bypass) rather than
  // propagating the error. This prevents engine outages from blocking rate-limited commands.
  // Errors are logged at Warn for operator visibility. See PR #88 review discussion.

But the actual code immediately below does:

  if err != nil {
      return false, err   // <— error IS propagated
  }

The comment's stated design intention directly contradicts the code. A reader relying on this comment to understand the bypass-check contract will have the wrong mental model. The caller (Enforce) does log the error at Warn, which partly matches the comment's intent — but the propagation itself contradicts the claim.

The hasBypass doc comment also states 'On evaluation error, returns (false, err) (fail-closed: apply rate limiting)' which correctly describes the code. The inline comment is the contradiction.

Fix: Remove or rewrite the inline comment to accurately describe what the function does (propagates the error to the caller, which decides whether to log and continue).","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:13:16Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:13:16Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.42","title":"hasBypass in rate_limit_middleware.go uses fmt.Errorf where oops is available and used elsewhere","description":"In internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go, the hasBypass helper (line ~12159 in diff) uses a raw fmt.Errorf to surface infrastructure failures:

    return false, fmt.Errorf("infrastructure failure during bypass check: %s", decision.Reason())

The rest of the file imports oops and uses it throughout (NewAccessRequest errors are wrapped with oops.With in access.go). Consistently using oops.Errorf here would:
1. Add namespace/context attributes visible in logs and error chains
2. Allow callers to inspect the error via oops.AsOops if needed
3. Match the style of every other error created in this package

Suggested replacement:
    return false, oops.With("reason", decision.Reason()).Errorf("infrastructure failure during bypass check")

This is consistent with how CheckCapability wraps the same decision.Reason() in access.go.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:16:37Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:16:37Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.5","title":"Dispatcher oops.AsOops ignores bool return — silent misclassification if non-oops error leaks","description":"In internal/command/dispatcher.go around line 173 in the new code, the capability check does:

  oopsErr, _ := oops.AsOops(capErr)
  if oopsErr.Code() == CodePermissionDenied {

The bool return from oops.AsOops is silently discarded. If oops.AsOops fails (returns false), oopsErr is a zero-value OopsError with an empty Code(), so the else branch fires and StatusEngineFailure is recorded — which is actually the correct fail-closed behavior. However, the discarded bool makes the intent unclear and creates a fragile dependency on zero-value behavior.

Since CheckCapability always wraps errors with oops.Code(), this never triggers in practice. But it's better to make the intent explicit:

  oopsErr, ok := oops.AsOops(capErr)
  if ok && oopsErr.Code() == CodePermissionDenied {
      metrics.SetStatus(StatusPermissionDenied)
  } else {
      metrics.SetStatus(StatusEngineFailure)
  }

File: internal/command/dispatcher.go","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:04:08Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:04:08Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.29","title":"Decision.Attributes() doc comment misleading: claims pointer not modified after creation, but SetAttributes can be called post-NewDecision","description":"File: internal/access/policy/types/types.go

The Attributes() accessor doc comment reads:
  // The returned pointer is not modified after the decision is created.

This is misleading. SetAttributes() exists precisely to set the attributes field after NewDecision() is called (the engine builds decisions incrementally). The comment is technically describing mutation of the pointed-to struct (which is not done after creation), but a reader will likely interpret it as 'this field is set during construction and never changes' — which is false.

The SetPolicies() doc comment correctly explains why setters exist (incremental construction across package boundary). The Attributes() doc comment should be aligned with that explanation, or at minimum the claim about immutability after creation should be removed to avoid confusion.

Suggested fix:
  // Attributes returns the attribute bags used during evaluation.
  // May be nil if attribute resolution was not attempted.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:13:35Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:13:35Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.27","title":"engine.go Step 3 comment omits behavior change: partial bags now used instead of empty bags on resolve error","description":"File: internal/access/policy/engine.go, Step 3 block

Old code on error:
  bags = types.NewAttributeBags()   // reset to empty bags

New code on error (PR change):
  // bags retains the partial result from resolver.Resolve()
  slog.WarnContext(ctx, "attribute resolution failed", "error", resolveErr)
  // no reset — bags may contain partial attributes from providers that succeeded

The comment 'Step 3: Eager attribute resolution (non-fatal; bags may be partial when providers fail)' correctly describes the new behavior, but does not note that this is a behavioral change from the prior implementation (which fell back to empty bags). A developer debugging an unexpected policy decision that depends on attribute values will not know to look here for a changed semantic.

Additionally, the prior comment 'resolver already logs errors internally' was removed, but the resolver still logs individual provider errors. The new engine also logs at Warn. This creates a double-log for the same error (once in resolver, once in engine). The comment update does not note this.

Fix: Add a brief note that this deviates from the prior empty-bags fallback, and clarify the logging behavior to prevent confusion about duplicate log entries.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:13:26Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:13:26Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.12","title":"IsInfraFailure() relies on stringly-typed policyID prefix convention","description":"File: internal/access/policy/types/types.go, lines 3747-3752 (diff)

IsInfraFailure() detects infrastructure failures by checking whether policyID has the 'infra:' string prefix:

  func (d Decision) IsInfraFailure() bool {
      return strings.HasPrefix(d.policyID, "infra:")
  }

This means the distinction between a policy denial and an infrastructure failure is encoded entirely in the string value of an opaque ID field — a field whose primary purpose is to identify which policy matched. The invariant that 'infra failures have infra: policyIDs' is documented only in comments and in the constant definitions (ErrCodeSessionInvalid = "infra:session-invalid").

The test even documents the ambiguity explicitly:
  name: "allow decision cannot be infra failure",
  expected: true, // still detects prefix even if semantically wrong

Suggested fix: Make the failure cause a first-class enum value on Decision, either as a separate FailureCause field or by extending Effect with dedicated infra-failure variants (EffectInfraFailure). This would make IsInfraFailure() type-safe:

  type FailureCause int
  const (
      FailureCauseNone FailureCause = iota
      FailureCauseSessionInvalid
      FailureCauseSessionStoreError
      FailureCausePolicyCacheStale
  )

This is a suggestion, not a blocker — the current code is consistent and tests cover the cases, but the string prefix convention is fragile as the set of infra failures grows.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:08:46Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:08:46Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.16","title":"ResourceCharacter and SubjectCharacter have identical string values; type system cannot distinguish roles","description":"File: internal/access/prefix.go, lines 4026-4069 (diff)

The PR introduces ResourceCharacter = "character:" alongside the existing SubjectCharacter = "character:". The comment in CharacterResource() explicitly notes:

  // Note: ResourceCharacter has the same string value as SubjectCharacter ("character:").
  // This is intentional: a character can be both a subject and a resource.

The problem: because the string values are identical, a caller passing CharacterSubject(id) where CharacterResource(id) is expected (or vice versa) will not produce any compile-time or runtime error. The type system offers no protection.

This is made worse by the AccessRequest struct using plain string fields — there is nothing to enforce that Subject is built with a Subject* helper and Resource is built with a Resource* helper.

At minimum: a note in the AccessRequest type documentation should call out this ambiguity and recommend using the typed helpers. Longer term, newtypes (type Subject string, type Resource string) would make the role semantics enforcement compile-time safe.

This is a documentation/design suggestion, not a bug in the current code, since the engine evaluates both roles correctly regardless of which helper is used.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:09:20Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:09:20Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.15","title":"Prefix helper functions panic on empty ID; error return would be safer at call sites","description":"File: internal/access/prefix.go, lines 4052-4133 (diff)

CharacterSubject(), LocationResource(), CommandResource(), and all the other prefix helpers introduced in this PR panic on empty ID:

  func CharacterSubject(charID string) string {
      if charID == "" {
          panic("access.CharacterSubject: empty charID would bypass access control")
      }
      return SubjectCharacter + charID
  }

Panics are appropriate for programmer errors that should never occur in correct code (e.g., nil pointer dereferences in constructors). However, these functions are called with IDs that come from runtime data — ULID strings, command names, etc. — where a missing ID is a recoverable data error, not a programming invariant violation.

Call sites like command handlers receive IDs from session state and world queries. If a character's ID is zero/empty due to a bug in session hydration, the panic will crash the server goroutine rather than return an error to the user.

The engine's validateRequest() already handles the empty-field case gracefully (INVALID_REQUEST error). The helpers don't need to panic; they can return (string, error) or return an empty string and let the engine reject it downstream.

Contrast: the Decision constructor does NOT panic — it uses NewDecision() which correctly handles all invariants without panic.

Suggested fix: Change signature to (string, error) pattern consistent with the project's error handling conventions, or document clearly that these are meant to be called only after validation (and test with the validated IDs).","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:09:10Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:09:10Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.40","title":"canExecuteCommand in hostfunc/commands.go duplicates CheckCapability logic already in command/access.go","description":"internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go (canExecuteCommand, lines ~11382-11433 in diff) hand-rolls the same access evaluation logic that command/access.go's CheckCapability already encapsulates: NewAccessRequest, engine.Evaluate, IsInfraFailure detection, slog.ErrorContext, observability.RecordEngineFailure.

The two diverge in subtle ways (canExecuteCommand returns a (bool, bool) rather than error, and uses a different metric key), but the core pattern is identical. If CheckCapability is changed (e.g., logging fields, metric name), the hostfunc copy will silently drift.

Suggested simplification: extract a shared helper or refactor canExecuteCommand to call CheckCapability and inspect the returned oops error code, similar to how dispatcher.go already does:

    if capErr := command.CheckCapability(ctx, f.engine, subject, cap, "list_commands"); capErr \!= nil {
        oopsErr, _ := oops.AsOops(capErr)
        hadEngineError = hadEngineError || oopsErr.Code() \!= command.CodePermissionDenied
        return false, hadEngineError
    }

This would consolidate the three copies of the infrastructure-failure logging pattern (access.go, dispatcher.go, commands.go) into one.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:16:24Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:16:24Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-phq3.19","title":"No unit test for checkAccess with infra failure across entity types beyond LOCATION in service_helpers_test.go","description":"internal/world/service_helpers_test.go (the new TestCheckAccess suite) tests the checkAccess helper thoroughly for LOCATION and EXIT entity prefixes, including infra failure paths, context cancellation, and error wrapping. However, the service_test.go tests for CHARACTER, OBJECT, and SCENE entity operations (GetCharacter, CreateObject, MoveCharacter, AddSceneParticipant, etc.) only test the allow and explicit-deny paths — they do not test the engine-error or infra-failure paths that produce CHARACTER_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED, OBJECT_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED, or SCENE_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED codes.

The service_helpers_test.go tests cover checkAccess generically (via entityPrefix parameter), but the service_test.go integration tests only add the engine-error / infra-failure sub-cases to GetLocation (at line 13572-13615). The other service methods like GetCharacter (line 13015), MoveCharacter (line 13093), GetObject (line 12943), and AddSceneParticipant (line 13054) lack these sub-cases.

This is a suggestion rather than critical since checkAccess itself is well-tested. Adding representative engine-error cases for one CHARACTER operation (e.g., GetCharacter) and one SCENE operation would complete the coverage picture.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T00:10:36Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T00:10:36Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

