{"id":"holomush-e41x.3","title":"who handler circuit breaker overcounts skipped sessions by up to maxEngineErrors","description":"In internal/command/handlers/who.go, when the circuit breaker fires at the top of the loop:

    if engineErrorCount >= maxEngineErrors {
        errorCount += len(sessions) - i   // session i not yet processed
        break
    }

Session at index i has not been processed yet. It might succeed, be a normal not-found skip, or be an engine error. Adding it unconditionally to errorCount overstates the error count by at least 1 (and up to maxEngineErrors players that were counted as engine errors in the previous iterations are now also counted in the "skipped" batch).

Concretely: with maxEngineErrors=3 and 10 sessions, if sessions 0,1,2 all fail, on iteration i=3 the check fires and adds len(sessions)-3 = 7 to errorCount. But errorCount already has 3 from the previous iterations, giving 10. However only 3 sessions actually produced errors — the other 7 are genuinely skipped due to the breaker.

The notification message "N players could not be displayed" will overcount. This is a minor UX issue, not a security issue.

Fix: Use errorCount += len(sessions) - i - 1 (exclude the current not-yet-processed session) if the breaker fires at the start of a loop body, or restructure so the breaker fires only at the end of each error-counting iteration.

Location: internal/command/handlers/who.go, WhoHandler function.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T12:45:01Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T12:45:01Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-e41x.10","title":"G706 gosec suppression is global — will silence log injection warnings in future non-slog code","description":".golangci.yaml suppresses gosec G706 (log injection) for all .go files via path: '.go$'. The comment justification is sound for slog, but the suppression is global and will apply to any future file that uses fmt.Printf or log.Printf with user-controlled strings.

A narrower suppression would be safer: either scope the exclusion to specific packages where slog is verified to be the only logger, or add a linting rule that enforces slog-only usage (e.g., forbidigo or a custom depguard rule for log.Printf). This would let G706 catch regressions if a developer adds a non-structured log statement.

