{"id":"holomush-e41x.4","title":"canExecuteCommand returns (false, hadError=true) for infra failures without distinct error signal to listCommandsFn","description":"In internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go, canExecuteCommand conflates two distinct deny cases in its return:

    if !decision.IsAllowed() {
        if decision.IsInfraFailure() {
            hadError = true
        }
        return false, hadError  // same return for policy-deny and infra-deny
    }

When a command is denied by policy, hadError=false and (false, false) is returned.
When denied by infrastructure failure, hadError=true and (false, true) is returned.

The listCommandsFn caller uses hadError to set the incomplete flag. This is correct behavior: infra failures hide commands from the list and mark it incomplete.

However, the function docstring says "hadError is true if any engine.Evaluate call returned an error" — this is incomplete, since it is also true when engine.Evaluate returns no error but the decision.IsInfraFailure() is true. The discrepancy between the doc and the implementation could mislead maintainers.

Additionally, there is no circuit-breaker in canExecuteCommand: if every command check produces an infra failure, the engine will be called O(n_commands * n_capabilities) times before hadEngineError is set. Under a degraded engine, this amplifies load.

Suggested fix for documentation: update the hadError doc to "hadError is true if any engine evaluation failed (returned error or indicated infrastructure failure)".
For load amplification: consider early-exit after maxEngineErrors in listCommandsFn's loop, similar to who.go.

Location: internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go, canExecuteCommand and listCommandsFn.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T12:45:15Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T12:45:15Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-gk8b.9","title":"Decision.SetPolicies does not defensive-copy, asymmetric with Policies() getter","description":"File: internal/access/policy/types/types.go

The Policies() getter (line ~140 in the new code) returns a defensive copy:

    func (d Decision) Policies() []PolicyMatch {
        cp := make([]PolicyMatch, len(d.policies))
        copy(cp, d.policies)
        return cp
    }

But SetPolicies() stores the reference directly without copying:

    func (d *Decision) SetPolicies(p []PolicyMatch) {
        d.policies = p
    }

This creates an asymmetry: if the engine (or any caller) retains and later mutates the slice passed to SetPolicies, the Decision's internal state silently changes. The defensive copy in Policies() becomes meaningless because the data can be corrupted through the unprotected write path.

Since this is a security-relevant type (access control decisions), mutation after construction could lead to audit log inconsistencies or incorrect decision reporting.

Suggested fix: Add defensive copy in SetPolicies:

    func (d *Decision) SetPolicies(p []PolicyMatch) {
        d.policies = make([]PolicyMatch, len(p))
        copy(d.policies, p)
    }

The same applies to SetAttributes if AttributeBags has mutable internal state, though pointer semantics there may be intentional.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T14:23:06Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T14:23:06Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-gk8b.11","title":"nolint:wrapcheck justification in hasBypass is inaccurate — error is logged, not wrapped","description":"File: internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go, lines in hasBypass()

Two nolint directives say 'will be wrapped by caller':

    //nolint:wrapcheck // Constructor error, will be wrapped by caller
    return false, err

    //nolint:wrapcheck // Engine error, will be wrapped by caller
    return false, err

But the caller (Enforce method) only logs the error and drops it:

    bypass, err := r.hasBypass(ctx, subject)
    if err != nil {
        slog.WarnContext(ctx, "rate limit bypass check failed", ...)
        observability.RecordEngineFailure("rate_limit_bypass")
        // Continue to rate limiting check below (fail-closed)
    }

The error is never wrapped. The nolint justification is misleading. The project's golangci config requires nolint explanations to be accurate (nolintlint with require-explanation: true).

Suggested fix: Change the nolint comments to accurately describe why wrapping is not needed:
    //nolint:wrapcheck // Error is logged and dropped by caller (fail-closed to rate limiting)","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T14:23:15Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T14:23:15Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-gk8b.4","title":"who handler circuit breaker counter does not distinguish between trip-threshold call and subsequent calls","description":"The who handler circuit breaker test (TestWhoHandler_CircuitBreakerTripsOnConsecutiveEngineErrors) uses Maybe() on all 5 mock engine expectations. This means the test cannot distinguish between 3 calls reaching the engine and only 1–2 calls. If the circuit breaker tripped at 1 or 2 errors instead of 3, the test would still pass because the output assertion only checks the final count and log message.

A stronger test would use EXPECT().Times(3) (or atMost) on the engine calls to assert that the engine is called exactly 3 times before the circuit trips, verifying the maxEngineErrors threshold is respected. The current test passes even if the circuit trips at 1 failure.

