{"id":"holomush-gk8b.46","title":"PlayerMessage missing _ACCESS_DENIED suffix normalization causes wrong user-facing message in SetHandler","description":"PlayerMessage in internal/command/errors.go normalizes _ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED suffix codes but does NOT normalize _ACCESS_DENIED suffix codes. The world service checkAccess helper generates entity-prefixed denial codes (LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED, OBJECT_ACCESS_DENIED, CHARACTER_ACCESS_DENIED, SCENE_ACCESS_DENIED, EXAMINE_ACCESS_DENIED) that wrap ErrPermissionDenied.

**The bug:** SetHandler in internal/command/handlers/objects.go (line ~8124-8126) explicitly passes through ErrPermissionDenied errors:

```go
if errors.Is(err, world.ErrPermissionDenied) {
    return err // passes OBJECT_ACCESS_DENIED directly
}
```

These codes don't match CodePermissionDenied ("PERMISSION_DENIED") in the PlayerMessage switch statement, so they fall through to the default case, returning "Something went wrong. Try again." instead of "You don't have permission to do that."

**Fix options:**
1. Add suffix normalization in PlayerMessage:
```go
if strings.HasSuffix(code, "_ACCESS_DENIED") {
    code = CodePermissionDenied
}
```

2. Or in SetHandler, re-wrap with CodePermissionDenied before returning:
```go
if errors.Is(err, world.ErrPermissionDenied) {
    return oops.Code(command.CodePermissionDenied).Wrap(err)
}
```

Option 1 is more consistent with the existing pattern for _ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED.

**Impact:** Players who attempt to set a property on something they don't have access to will see a generic error message rather than an actionable permission denied message.

**Confidence:** 87","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T18:48:21Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T18:48:21Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-gk8b.44","title":"hasBypass error returned without oops context wrapping","description":"In internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go, the hasBypass method returns errors from NewAccessRequest and engine.Evaluate unwrapped (annotated with //nolint:wrapcheck). The caller Enforce logs the error with the subject, action, resource, and command via slog.WarnContext, so the operational context is not lost in logs. However, the returned error object itself carries no structured context (no oops.With fields for subject or capability).

If any future caller captures this error for programmatic inspection (errors.Is/As, oops.AsOops), they will find a bare error with no traceability back to which subject or capability triggered the failure.

The fix is simple: wrap the error with oops context before returning, rather than relying on the caller to log context:
  return false, oops.With('subject', subject).With('capability', CapabilityRateLimitBypass).Wrap(err)

This also removes the need for the nolint directive.

File: internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go, hasBypass method.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T18:46:03Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T18:46:03Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-3cm7.9","title":"GetRole in CharacterProvider uses 'character:' prefix but tests/callers still use 'char:' prefix for AssignRole — silent role miss in ABAC engine","description":"In internal/access/policy/attribute/character.go, CharacterProvider.resolve() builds subjectID as 'character:' + char.ID.String() and calls p.roleResolver.GetRole(subjectID). StaticAccessControl.GetRole() looks up by the exact key stored in the subjects map. However, StaticAccessControl.AssignRole() accepts any subject string without normalization. All existing tests (internal/access/static_test.go lines 75-530) still call AssignRole with 'char:' prefix (e.g., ac.AssignRole("char:player1", "player")). As a result, GetRole("character:<id>") will never find roles stored under 'char:<id>', so all characters will resolve to the default 'player' role during ABAC evaluation, silently defeating role-based policy enforcement.

This is a migration correctness bug: subjects stored with 'char:' prefix and looked up with 'character:' prefix produce empty string from GetRole.

Fix: Either normalize the subject key in AssignRole (strip and re-prefix), or update all callers of AssignRole to use the new 'character:' prefix. The test file at internal/access/static_test.go has ~20 occurrences that need updating. Production callers should be audited — grep shows only tests call AssignRole with 'char:' in the current worktree.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-10T20:39:46Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-10T20:39:46Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-0hag.6","title":"PlayerMessage() suffix path for entity-prefixed _ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED codes not tested","description":"The new suffix-matching branch in PlayerMessage() (errors.go:6259) handles entity-prefixed codes like LOCATION_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED, CHARACTER_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED, etc. via strings.HasSuffix(code, "_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED"). However, errors_test.go only adds a test case for the exact CodeAccessEvaluationFailed constant, not for any of the world-service entity-prefixed variants (LOCATION_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED, EXIT_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED, etc.).

