{"id":"holomush-0hag.13","title":"createObject/createLocation missing ErrPermissionDenied passthrough — denial logged as system error","description":"In internal/command/handlers/objects.go, the createObject (~line 68) and createLocation (~line 90) functions check for ErrAccessEvaluationFailed before the logging path, but do NOT check for ErrPermissionDenied. When CreateObject or CreateLocation returns a permission-denied error, the code falls through to slog.ErrorContext('create object: CreateObject failed') and wraps the error in WORLD_ERROR, masking it.

This causes two problems:
1. Observability: A normal policy denial (player lacks write permission) is logged as slog.Error with the system-error message, polluting monitoring dashboards with false alerts.
2. Player message: writeOutputWithWorldError wraps in WORLD_ERROR; PlayerMessage returns the custom 'Failed to create object/location' world-error message instead of 'You don't have permission to do that.' The suffix match for '_ACCESS_DENIED' in PlayerMessage never fires because the error is re-wrapped.

Compare with SetHandler (~line 164) and propertyQuerier.GetLocation/GetObject/UpdateLocation/UpdateObject which all correctly check both ErrAccessEvaluationFailed AND ErrPermissionDenied before the logging path.

Fix: add an errors.Is(err, world.ErrPermissionDenied) passthrough check in both createObject and createLocation, immediately before the slog.ErrorContext call, matching the pattern used in the set handler:

  if errors.Is(err, world.ErrPermissionDenied) {
    return err
  }","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T00:05:36Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T00:05:36Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-0hag.15","title":"createObject/createLocation silently drop ErrPermissionDenied, wrapping it as WORLD_ERROR","description":"In internal/command/handlers/objects.go, the createObject() and createLocation() functions check for world.ErrAccessEvaluationFailed before falling through to the error-logging/WORLD_ERROR path, but they do NOT check for world.ErrPermissionDenied.

When the policy engine cleanly denies access to CreateObject or CreateLocation (a normal policy denial, not an infra failure), the returned error wraps world.ErrPermissionDenied with an OBJECT_ACCESS_DENIED or LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED code. Because this error is not caught and passed through, it falls into the slog.ErrorContext path and gets re-wrapped as WORLD_ERROR, which:
1. Logs a spurious 'create object: CreateObject failed' error for every normal permission denial
2. Loses the specific access-denied code, so PlayerMessage() cannot generate the right player-facing message

All other call sites that handle world service errors (look.go, move.go, SetHandler, propertyQuerier, propertyMutator) check BOTH ErrAccessEvaluationFailed AND ErrPermissionDenied before the fallthrough.

Fix: Add the ErrPermissionDenied passthrough to both createObject() and createLocation() in internal/command/handlers/objects.go, matching the pattern used in every other error-handling site in the same file:

  if errors.Is(err, world.ErrPermissionDenied) {
      return err //nolint:wrapcheck // preserve access-denied code
  }","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T00:06:01Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T00:06:01Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-0hag.26","title":"[code] who.go circuit breaker logs warning BEFORE checking threshold, not after tripping","description":"File: internal/command/handlers/who.go, WhoHandler

In the who handler, the circuit breaker trip warning is logged inside the engineErrorCount check:

  if errors.Is(err, world.ErrAccessEvaluationFailed) {
      errorCount++
      engineErrorCount++
      if engineErrorCount >= maxEngineErrors {
          slog.WarnContext(ctx, "who handler circuit breaker tripped: aborting after engine failures",
              "skipped_sessions", len(sessions)-i-1,
          )
      }
      continue
  }

But the actual circuit breaker abort (the break) is at the TOP of the loop:

  if engineErrorCount >= maxEngineErrors {
      errorCount += len(sessions) - i
      break
  }

This means the log fires on the Nth failure but the break happens on the (N+1)th iteration. The 'skipped_sessions' count in the log is therefore off by one — it will say (len-i-1) skipped but in fact i+1 more will be skipped because the break happens on the next loop entry, adding len(sessions)-i to errorCount. The circuit breaker log fires at the correct threshold but the skipped count is wrong.

Suggested fix: Log the circuit breaker warning at the top of the loop when the threshold is detected (same location as the break), so the message and skipped count are consistent.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T00:32:08Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T00:32:08Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-c3ww.1","title":"Silent empty who list when engine consistently denies GetCharacter","description":"In internal/command/handlers/who.go (WhoHandler), ErrPermissionDenied errors from world.GetCharacter are silently skipped (continue without incrementing errorCount). This is intentional for individual characters that a subject genuinely cannot see, but creates a silent failure mode at the operator level: if the engine consistently returns policy-deny decisions (not infra failures, not Go errors) for ALL GetCharacter calls—e.g. due to a broken policy seed that accidentally denies everything—the who list shows 0 online players with no error notice to the user and no log at error/warn level. The operator has no signal that something is wrong. The same pattern exists in findCharacterByName in boot.go.

Relevant code path (who.go ~line 130):
  if errors.Is(err, world.ErrNotFound) || errors.Is(err, world.ErrPermissionDenied) {
    continue  // no errorCount++, no log
  }

The distinction between 'policy denied for this character' (expected) and 'policy denied for ALL characters' (broken) is not tracked. A policy misconfiguration that returns deny instead of infra-failure for every call would produce: zero visible players, no error count, no user message, no log entry at warn/error.

Suggested fix: Add a per-handler metric or log sampling that fires if the ratio of ErrPermissionDenied skips to total sessions exceeds a threshold (e.g., all sessions skipped). Alternatively, track ErrPermissionDenied skips separately from ErrNotFound skips and log a warning if 100% of sessions were skipped due to permission denied—this is anomalous even in a correct system.

