{"id":"holomush-c3ww.18","title":"engine.go: audit errors silently discarded with blank identifier assignment","description":"Four audit log errors in internal/access/policy/engine.go are discarded with '_ = err' / '_ = auditErr' at lines 72, 133, 164, and 201. None of these are logged before discard.

File: internal/access/policy/engine.go
Lines: 72, 133, 164, 201

Problem: The comment at line 71 says 'Log error but don't fail the decision', but the implementation does not log — it just drops the error completely. Audit failures for security decisions (including denials and system bypasses) produce zero operational signal. An operator cannot distinguish between 'audit logging is working normally' and 'audit logging is completely broken'.

Affected code pattern (repeated at each site):
  if auditErr := e.audit.Log(ctx, entry); auditErr != nil {
      _ = auditErr  // no log, no metric
  }

Suggested fix: Replace each blank discard with a slog.Error or errutil.LogError call, e.g.:
  if auditErr := e.audit.Log(ctx, entry); auditErr != nil {
      slog.Error("audit log failed", "effect", entry.Effect, "subject", entry.Subject, "error", auditErr)
  }

Note: The audit.Logger already has Prometheus counters (failuresCounter) for its internal failures, but those do not fire when the Logger.Log() call itself errors — they only fire for write failures inside the logger. The engine-level discard is a separate gap.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T02:06:36Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T02:06:36Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-c3ww.21","title":"engine.go session resolution swallows underlying store error without logging","description":"In internal/access/policy/engine.go, Step 2 (session resolution) at lines 87-101 catches errors from ResolveSession() but returns nil error in all cases, with no logging of the underlying error when it is NOT SESSION_INVALID.

File: internal/access/policy/engine.go:87-101

Problem: When the session store fails (network error, timeout, DB unavailable), the error is used only to pick a denial reason string ('session store error' vs 'session invalid'), then the original error is discarded and the function returns (deny decision, nil). This means:
1. The operator gets a deny decision logged to the audit trail (good), but
2. The underlying infrastructure error that caused the deny is never logged anywhere.
3. An attacker repeatedly hitting a degraded session store receives the same deny as an expired session, making the store failure invisible in application logs.

Affected code:
  characterID, err := e.sessions.ResolveSession(ctx, sessionID)
  if err != nil {
      oopsErr, ok := oops.AsOops(err)
      var decision types.Decision
      if ok && oopsErr.Code() == "SESSION_INVALID" {
          decision = types.NewDecision(types.EffectDefaultDeny, "session invalid", ...)
      } else {
          decision = types.NewDecision(types.EffectDefaultDeny, "session store error", ...)
          // ← original err is never logged
      }
      return decision, nil  // ← err discarded
  }

Suggested fix: For the non-SESSION_INVALID branch (infrastructure error), add a slog.Error or errutil.LogError before constructing the decision:
  slog.Error("session store error during access evaluation", "session_id", sessionID, "error", err)","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T02:07:11Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T02:07:11Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-c3ww.20","title":"listCommandsFn uses context.Background() instead of caller context, losing cancellation","description":"In internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go, listCommandsFn creates a fresh context.Background() at line 79 instead of using a context from the caller, then passes it to access.Check() calls in canExecuteCommand().

File: internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go:79

Problem: The Lua host function is called within a plugin execution context that may be request-scoped or have cancellation signals. By using context.Background(), access control checks inside canExecuteCommand() ignore any cancellation or deadline from the calling request context. If the plugin host has a timeout (e.g., per-event processing deadline), the access check will not respect it, potentially causing goroutines to block past their intended lifetime.

Affected code:
  ctx := context.Background()
  // Filter commands by character capabilities
  var filtered []command.CommandEntry
  for _, cmd := range commands {
      if f.canExecuteCommand(ctx, subject, cmd) { ... }
  }

This is likely a Lua GFunction binding limitation (the LGFunction signature provides no context), but the fix is to capture the context from the enclosing scope (the plugin delivery context) when the function is registered, rather than creating a Background context at call time.

Suggested fix: Have the option-setter (WithAccessControl or the function registration) capture the per-event context when available, or pass a stored context from the Functions struct. At minimum, document why Background() is intentional if it is.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T02:06:58Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T02:06:58Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-c3ww.19","title":"ReplayWAL truncates file even when some entries fail to replay, causing data loss","description":"In internal/access/policy/audit/logger.go, ReplayWAL() at line ~297-306 continues iterating after individual WriteSync failures and then unconditionally truncates the WAL at line 306.

File: internal/access/policy/audit/logger.go:297-306

Problem: If any WAL entries fail to replay (DB down, write error, unmarshal error), those entries are logged at slog.Error and skipped, but the WAL is still truncated at the end. This permanently discards audit records that were never successfully written to the backend. Audit records for denied access decisions are lost with no recovery path.

Affected code:
  if err := l.writer.WriteSync(ctx, entry); err != nil {
      slog.Error("failed to replay WAL entry", ...)
      failuresCounter.WithLabelValues("wal_replay_failed").Inc()
      // Continue with other entries  ← drops the entry
  }
  lines++
  ...
  // Truncate WAL on success  ← truncates even on partial failure
  if err := os.Truncate(l.walPath, 0); err != nil { ... }

Suggested fix: Track whether any replay failures occurred. If failures > 0, either:
  (a) Do not truncate — leave WAL intact so a future replay attempt can retry the failed entries, OR
  (b) Rewrite the WAL with only the failed entries before truncating the full file.

Option (a) is simpler and safer for an audit trail.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T02:06:47Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T02:06:47Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-c3ww.37","title":"canExecuteCommand missing RecordEngineFailure on request construction error","description":"In internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go canExecuteCommand(), when NewAccessRequest fails (line ~148-153), the code logs the error and sets hadError=true but does NOT call observability.RecordEngineFailure(). The subsequent Evaluate error path (line ~156-162) correctly calls RecordEngineFailure.

This is inconsistent with the pattern used in both checkAccess (world/service.go) and CheckCapability (command/access.go), where request construction failures always record engine failure metrics.

Fix: Add observability.RecordEngineFailure("command_capability_check") in the NewAccessRequest error branch. Confidence: 80.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T02:34:59Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T02:34:59Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-c3ww.40","title":"Attribute resolution fail-closed change returns both denied Decision AND non-nil error -- callers must handle both","description":"In engine.go Step 3 (diff lines 2746-2759), when attribute resolution fails, the engine now returns BOTH a DefaultDeny decision AND a non-nil error:

    d := types.NewDecision(types.EffectDefaultDeny, 'attribute resolution failed', 'infra:attribute-resolution-failed')
    return d, oops.With(...).Wrap(resolveErr)

This is the only code path that returns both a meaningful Decision AND a non-nil error. All other error returns use types.Decision{} (zero value). The checkAccess helper (diff line 14186) and CheckCapability (diff line 5487) both check 'if err != nil' first and treat it as an evaluation failure, ignoring the Decision entirely.

This is not a bug per se -- the error takes precedence. But the pattern is inconsistent: in one path, the Decision is populated but unused; in all others, it's zero. If a future caller checks the Decision before the error, they'd get a deny with infra metadata, which could be confusing.

Suggestion: For consistency, return types.Decision{} when returning a non-nil error (same as all other error paths), or document that the Decision in error returns carries informational metadata only.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T02:38:05Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T02:38:05Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.8","title":"dispatcher.go logs Evaluate() error but cannot distinguish eval failure from policy deny at call site","description":"In internal/command/dispatcher.go, when Evaluate() returns an error, the code logs the error and then falls through to the same deny path as a legitimate policy denial:

  if evalErr != nil {
      slog.ErrorContext(ctx, "access evaluation failed", ...)
  }
  if evalErr != nil || !decision.IsAllowed() {
      metrics.SetStatus(StatusPermissionDenied)
      err = ErrPermissionDenied(parsed.Name, cap)
      return err
  }

The user receives an ErrPermissionDenied response regardless of whether access was denied by policy or by an engine infrastructure failure. The StatusPermissionDenied metric is also recorded in both cases, making it impossible to distinguish legitimate denials from engine failures in metrics/alerting.

The same pattern exists in boot.go.

Suggested improvements:
1. Use a distinct metric status (e.g., StatusEvalError) when evalErr != nil, so dashboards can detect engine failures separately from policy denials.
2. Consider returning a distinct error type (e.g., ErrEvalFailed) so that callers and telemetry can distinguish the two cases.

This is an observability concern — the behavior (deny on error) is correct and fail-closed, but the error/metric path loses the distinction between two very different failure modes.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T14:05:08Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T14:05:08Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.4","title":"world/service.go checkAccess does not wrap ErrPermissionDenied with oops code when engine errors","description":"In internal/world/service.go, the new checkAccess helper returns the bare ErrPermissionDenied sentinel (errors.New) when the engine returns an error:

  if err != nil {
      slog.ErrorContext(ctx, "access evaluation failed", ...)
      return ErrPermissionDenied  // bare sentinel, no oops context
  }

But callers immediately wrap this with an oops code:
  if err := s.checkAccess(...); err != nil {
      return nil, oops.Code("LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED").Wrap(err)
  }

The problem is that the original engine error is lost — it's logged but NOT wrapped into the returned error chain. The caller sees LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED wrapping ErrPermissionDenied, with no link back to the engine error. Any error code, With() fields, or stack trace from the engine error are completely discarded.

This means that when the ABAC engine fails (e.g., SESSION_STORE_ERROR), the caller only sees a generic ACCESS_DENIED, with no way to distinguish a policy denial from an infrastructure failure in error handling code or tests.

Suggested fix: wrap the engine error in the return:
  if err != nil {
      slog.ErrorContext(ctx, "access evaluation failed", ...)
      return oops.Code("ACCESS_EVAL_FAILED").With("subject", subject).Wrap(err)
  }

This preserves the error chain and lets callers distinguish evaluation failures from policy denials.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T14:04:36Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T14:04:36Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.7","title":"RateLimitMiddleware.Enforce has vestigial nil-receiver guard that can no longer be triggered","description":"File: internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go, Enforce method, line 43.

  if r == nil || r.limiter == nil {
      return nil
  }

This PR changed NewRateLimitMiddleware to return (middleware, error) instead of potentially returning nil. A nil return now only happens on error, and callers that ignore the error get a nil pointer — which would panic when calling Enforce anyway, not reach this guard.

The r == nil branch is now dead code that misleads readers into thinking nil RateLimitMiddleware is a supported state. This is a YAGNI issue introduced in this PR (the guard was already present in main, but the PR made it unreachable in correct usage while not removing it).

Suggested fix: remove the r == nil check from Enforce and add a comment that callers must not pass a nil receiver, or add a precondition panic.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T14:05:07Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T14:05:07Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.5","title":"GetCharactersByLocation uses prefixCharacter for a location resource, producing misleading error codes","description":"File: internal/world/service.go, around the GetCharactersByLocation function.

The checkAccess call uses prefixCharacter for a request whose resource is a location:

  resource := access.LocationResource(locationID.String())
  if err := s.checkAccess(ctx, subjectID, "list_characters", resource, prefixCharacter); err != nil {

This produces error codes CHARACTER_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED and CHARACTER_ACCESS_DENIED even though the resource being checked is a location. Both codes are in the entityAccessEvalFailedCodes / entityAccessDeniedCodes allowlists in errors.go so PlayerMessage handles them correctly — there is no user-visible bug. However, the mismatch makes structured log queries and metrics confusing: operators searching for LOCATION_* errors will miss failures from this path.

Suggested fix: change prefixCharacter to prefixLocation here to align the error code with the resource being protected. The entityAccessEvalFailedCodes and entityAccessDeniedCodes allowlists already contain LOCATION_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED and LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED, so no other changes are needed.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T14:04:55Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T14:04:55Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.9","title":"Examine* methods authorize after fetching — entity existence leakable to unauthorized callers","description":"ExamineLocation, ExamineObject, and ExamineCharacter in internal/world/service.go fetch from the repository before calling checkAccess. This means an unauthorized caller can distinguish 'entity does not exist' (NOT_FOUND) from 'entity exists but access denied' (ACCESS_DENIED) by observing error codes. No test documents or explicitly asserts this ordering as intentional design, nor is there a test that verifies the boundary: e.g., that ExamineLocation on a non-existent location with an unauthorized subject returns NOT_FOUND (not ACCESS_DENIED).

This leaks entity existence to unauthorized subjects and is worth either:
1. Adding a comment in service.go explaining the intentional ordering (data-fetch-before-auth is acceptable here because locations/objects/characters are considered non-sensitive for existence), or
2. Adding a test that explicitly covers the 'unauthorized on non-existent resource' case to document the expected behavior.

Example gap (no existing test covers this case):
  engine := policytest.NewGrantEngine() // no grants → default deny
  _, err := svc.ExamineLocation(ctx, subjectID, charID, nonExistentLocID)
  // Current behavior: returns NOT_FOUND (existence is leaked)
  // vs auth-first: would return ACCESS_DENIED

Affected methods: ExamineLocation (service.go:818), ExamineObject (service.go:876), ExamineCharacter (service.go:931).","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T14:07:47Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T14:07:47Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.18","title":"protect-main.sh Claude hook deleted without replacement","description":".claude/hooks/protect-main.sh is deleted in this PR with no replacement. MEMORY.md notes this hook was 'patched to handle detached HEAD via .jj detection', suggesting it was previously modified. The hook prevented AI agents from editing files directly on main.

