{"id":"holomush-wfza.22","title":"Attribute resolver errors no longer logged at provider level — debugging context degraded","description":"In internal/access/policy/attribute/resolver.go, safeResolve and safeResolveEnvironment previously called r.logger.Error at the point of provider failure (with namespace, resolve_type, entity_id context). This PR removes those log calls and instead returns the error for the engine to log via errutil.LogErrorContext. The engine log (in engine.go) only includes subject, action, resource — not the provider namespace or resolve_type that failed. The oops context fields on the returned error do contain namespace/resolve_type/entity_id, but only structured log implementations that extract oops context fields will surface them.

Impact: When a single provider fails among multiple (the resolveEntity function continues to the next provider after appending to errs), the engine receives a combined errors.Join error with multiple errors. The engine log will show the combined error but not which specific provider(s) failed. This makes production debugging of attribute provider failures harder.

Suggestion: Either restore per-provider logging (at debug/warn level) before returning the error, or ensure the engine logs the error with sufficient context by using errutil.LogError (which extracts oops context fields) rather than a plain slog call.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T20:14:03Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T20:14:03Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.20","title":"entityPrefix/PlayerMessage allowlist coupling risk: new entity types silently fall through","description":"internal/world/service.go defines entityPrefix constants (prefixLocation, prefixExit, prefixObject, prefixCharacter, prefixScene) and builds error codes dynamically: failCode = string(prefix) + '_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED'.

internal/command/errors.go maintains two explicit allowlists (entityAccessEvalFailedCodes, entityAccessDeniedCodes) that must stay in sync with the entityPrefix constants. If a new entityPrefix is added in service.go without updating the allowlists in errors.go, PlayerMessage() will silently fall through to the default 'Something went wrong. Try again.' response for that entity type, and the slog.Warn('unhandled error code') will be logged.

The two files are decoupled — there is no compile-time guarantee they agree. Consider adding a test (or a comment cross-referencing both locations) that verifies the two sets are in sync, e.g., via a TestPlayerMessage_EntityPrefixCoverage test that iterates all known entity prefixes.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T20:13:16Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T20:13:16Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.35","title":"[errors] ReplayWAL doc.go example silently drops error return","description":"The doc.go package example for audit.Logger silently drops the ReplayWAL return value:

    logger.ReplayWAL(ctx)

This is located at internal/access/policy/audit/doc.go:61. The PartialReplayError type introduced in this PR is a meaningful return value — it signals that some WAL entries failed to replay and the WAL was rewritten with the failed entries for retry. Callers that ignore the error will not know replay was partial and cannot alert or log the gap.

Additionally, no test covers the PartialReplayError path. The only ReplayWAL test (TestAuditLogger_ReplayWAL in logger_test.go:285) tests the full-success path only.

Suggested fix:
1. Update the doc.go example to show proper error handling:
   if err := logger.ReplayWAL(ctx); err != nil {
       var partial *audit.PartialReplayError
       if errors.As(err, &partial) {
           slog.Warn('WAL replay partial', 'failed', partial.FailedCount, 'total', partial.TotalCount)
       } else {
           slog.Error('WAL replay failed', 'error', err)
       }
   }
2. Add a test that covers the PartialReplayError path (writer fails on some entries).","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T21:59:41Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T21:59:41Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.36","title":"[code] AccessPolicyEngine type alias in production hostfunc package exported for test convenience","description":"internal/plugin/hostfunc/commands.go defines:

    // AccessPolicyEngine is a type alias re-exported for integration test convenience.
    type AccessPolicyEngine = types.AccessPolicyEngine

This exports test infrastructure from a production package. The only consumer is help_integration_test.go:329 which uses it as a parameter type. Tests can import types.AccessPolicyEngine directly from internal/access/policy/types without needing a re-export from hostfunc.

Per YAGNI, this alias should be removed from the production package. The integration test should import the interface directly from the types package.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T21:59:43Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T21:59:43Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.56","title":"Attribute resolver errors silently discarded — policies evaluated with incomplete attributes","description":"In internal/access/policy/engine.go lines 108-113, attribute resolution errors are silently discarded and evaluation continues with an empty attribute bag:

    bags, err := e.resolver.Resolve(ctx, req)
    if err != nil {
        // Provider errors don't fail evaluation — continue with what we have
        // (resolver already logs errors internally)
        bags = types.NewAttributeBags()
    }

The comment claims 'resolver already logs errors internally' but resolver.Resolve() in attribute/resolver.go always returns nil error (line 142: 'return bags, nil') — individual provider errors are caught by safeResolve() and logged there, but they never surface as a top-level resolver error. So the engine-level error branch is dead code — it will never fire — yet it establishes the misleading pattern that attribute failures are acceptable.

The deeper problem: if a future change makes Resolve() return errors, or if the re-entrance panic is replaced with an error, evaluation silently proceeds with empty bags. A policy that should grant access based on character.role will instead see no role attribute and default-deny. This is fail-closed from a security perspective, but it is a silent failure — no log entry captures that attributes were missing for this specific evaluation.

Fix: even if empty bags are acceptable, log a warning with the subject/action/resource when err != nil, so operators can correlate unexplained denials with attribute resolution failures.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:03Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:03Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.60","title":"rate_limit_middleware.go missing SPDX-License-Identifier header","description":"internal/command/rate_limit_middleware.go line 1 has only '// Copyright 2026 HoloMUSH Contributors' but is missing the required 'SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0' line.

CLAUDE.md requires: 'MUST include SPDX header — All .go, .sh, .proto files'

