{"id":"holomush-wfza.59","title":"WAL replay truncates file before confirming all entries were successfully replayed","description":"In internal/access/policy/audit/logger.go, ReplayWAL() (lines 264-313) continues past WriteSync failures for individual entries and truncates the WAL file at the end regardless:

    if err := l.writer.WriteSync(ctx, entry); err != nil {
        slog.Error("failed to replay WAL entry", ...)
        failuresCounter.WithLabelValues("wal_replay_failed").Inc()
        // Continue with other entries
    }
    // ...
    if err := os.Truncate(l.walPath, 0); err != nil { ... }

If any WriteSync calls fail during replay, those audit entries are silently lost when the WAL is truncated. For a write-ahead log whose purpose is durability of denied-access audit records, this is a correctness issue: the WAL provides the illusion of durability but entries can disappear if the writer is degraded during replay.

Fix: track whether any WriteSync calls failed. If failures occurred, do not truncate the WAL (or truncate only the successfully replayed prefix). At minimum, return an error so the caller knows replay was partial.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:20Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:20Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.63","title":"Cache.Start() is a no-op stub — production use will never get cache invalidation","description":"internal/access/policy/cache.go:199-205 — Cache.Start() is a documented placeholder that does nothing except log a warning:

  func (pc *Cache) Start(_ context.Context, connStr string) error {
      // This method would create a real PgListener. For now, it's a placeholder
      _ = connStr
      slog.Warn("Cache.Start called without real PG listener implementation")
      return nil
  }

If production code calls Start() (the natural wiring path), the policy cache will never receive LISTEN/NOTIFY invalidation events. After the stalenessThreshold (30s default), IsStale() returns true and ALL access requests will be denied (fail-closed). This would cause a complete access lockout 30 seconds after startup.

The correct method for both production and testing is StartWithListener(), but the public API presents Start() as the production entry point via its docstring ('The connStr should be a PostgreSQL connection string').

Risk: If any wiring code calls Start() instead of StartWithListener(), the system will lock everyone out within 30 seconds of boot.

Fix: Either implement Start() with a real PgListener, or document clearly that Start() must NOT be called in production and only StartWithListener() should be used.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:41Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:41Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.57","title":"Cache.Start() is a no-op stub that logs a warning but is not wired to fail startup","description":"internal/access/policy/cache.go lines 199-205: Cache.Start() ignores its connStr argument and returns nil (success) after logging a warning:

    func (pc *Cache) Start(_ context.Context, connStr string) error {
        _ = connStr
        slog.Warn("Cache.Start called without real PG listener implementation")
        return nil
    }

Any caller that invokes Cache.Start() believing LISTEN/NOTIFY is active will have a stale-after-30s cache with no invalidation. Because Start() returns nil, the caller has no signal that invalidation is disabled. The staleness check in Evaluate() will eventually deny all requests after 30 seconds of no reload.

This is a stub, but the error handling contract is misleading: returning nil implies success. If this method is meant to be a placeholder, it should either return an error ('not implemented') or panic with a clear message directing callers to use StartWithListener instead. The current behavior silently degrades the system.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:12Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-11T23:41:12Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-wfza.81","title":"No denial smoke test for list_characters on non-current location","description":"The seed_smoke_test.go adds TestSeedSmoke_AdminLocationListCharacters and TestSeedSmoke_BuilderLocationListCharacters (allow cases), but there is no new smoke test for the denial case: a player attempting list_characters on a location they are NOT currently in. The existing TestSeedSmoke_PlayerDeniedOtherLocationRead covers read denial on a non-current location, but after the compound-resource decomposition (location:<id>:characters → action=list_characters resource=location:<id>), the denial path for list_characters at a non-current location is a distinct policy evaluation path that is not exercised. A regression in the seed policy could silently allow listing characters in every room to any player without a test catching it.

File: internal/access/policy/seed_smoke_test.go (after line 3997 in diff)

Suggested addition:
  func TestSeedSmoke_PlayerDeniedListCharacters_NonCurrentLocation(t *testing.T) {
      // player is in locA but attempts list_characters on locB
      ...
      assert.False(t, decision.IsAllowed(), "player should NOT list characters at non-current location")
  }","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-12T00:21:45Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-12T00:21:45Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-sdno.34","title":"[code] Inconsistent oopsErr.Code() comparison patterns across changed files","description":"Two different patterns are used in the PR to compare oops error codes:

Pattern A (engine.go line 106, errors.go line 172): type assertion before comparison
    code, isStr := oopsErr.Code().(string)
    if isStr && code == "SESSION_INVALID" { ... }

Pattern B (dispatcher.go line 175): direct interface comparison
    if ok && oopsErr.Code() == CodePermissionDenied { ... }

Both work in Go because interface == compares type+value when both are the same concrete type. However Pattern B silently succeeds for a nil code (oopsErr.Code() returns nil) only if the right-hand side is also nil — it does not panic but produces a false negative.

Pattern A is more explicit and intention-revealing: it makes the type assumption visible and handles the nil case through the bool guard. The PR should standardize on one pattern.

Recommended: standardize on Pattern A (type assertion) throughout the new code in this PR for clarity and consistency.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-13T00:36:00Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-13T00:36:00Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-sdno.35","title":"[code] GetCharactersByLocation uses prefixLocation producing CHARACTER_QUERY_FAILED but error codes say LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED","description":"File: internal/world/service.go, GetCharactersByLocation method.

GetCharactersByLocation checks list_characters permission on a location resource:

    resource := access.LocationResource(locationID.String())
    if err := s.checkAccess(ctx, subjectID, "list_characters", resource, prefixLocation); err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }

This produces LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED or LOCATION_ACCESS_EVALUATION_FAILED on failure. However the error code prefix says LOCATION but the operation is conceptually about characters. The allowlist in command/errors.go includes LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED in entityAccessDeniedCodes — so PlayerMessage handles it correctly.

This is intentional per ADR #76 (the compound resource decomposition), and tests confirm it. No code change required. However it creates an observable discrepancy: GetCharactersByLocation failures appear in metrics/logs as LOCATION_ACCESS_DENIED, not CHARACTER_ACCESS_DENIED. Consider adding a comment near the checkAccess call explaining that the error code is LOCATION_* by design (the resource is the location, not the characters) to prevent future refactoring confusion.

This is a documentation/maintainability suggestion, not a blocking issue.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-13T00:36:10Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-13T00:36:10Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-sdno.32","title":"[code] doc.go example uses log.Printf instead of slog — violates project conventions","description":"File: internal/access/policy/audit/doc.go, diff line 356.

The updated doc example uses log.Printf for WAL replay error handling:

    if err := logger.ReplayWAL(ctx); err != nil {
        log.Printf("WAL replay: %v", err)
    }

The project mandates structured logging via slog (CLAUDE.md: 'Use structured logging (slog)'). The example should use slog.Error or slog.Warn to be consistent with the rest of the codebase and to set a good example for operators copying the pattern.

Suggested fix:
    if err := logger.ReplayWAL(ctx); err != nil {
        slog.Error("WAL replay failed", "error", err)
    }","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-13T00:35:49Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-13T00:35:49Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-sdno.53","title":"Dispatcher option loop does not short-circuit on first error, contradicting test comment","description":"In internal/command/dispatcher.go, the option processing loop sets d.optErr on failure but continues executing ALL remaining options before the error is checked. The test TestNewDispatcher_MultipleOptionErrors_ReturnsFirstError contains the comment 'This should NOT be called' on the second option function, but the second option IS called (it sets d.aliasCache) — the comment is incorrect and creates a false expectation.

Code pattern:
  for _, opt := range opts {
      opt(d)  // all options always run
  }
  if d.optErr != nil {
      return nil, d.optErr
  }

While the dispatcher is discarded on error so side-effects are benign today, the test comment creates a documentation bug that could mislead future maintainers into thinking options stop executing on the first error. If a future option has an expensive or impure side-effect, the silent continuation would be surprising.

Suggested fix: Either (1) break the loop on first error, or (2) remove the misleading 'should NOT be called' comment and replace it with 'is still called — all options run before error check'.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-13T01:14:37Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-13T01:14:37Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/88"}

{"id":"holomush-ycrv.3","title":"Disconnect always emits leave reason 'quit' regardless of actual disconnect cause","description":"In internal/grpc/server.go Disconnect, s.engine.HandleDisconnect is called with hardcoded reason 'quit' regardless of whether the disconnect was voluntary, a timeout, or a network drop. The spec acknowledges this deferral ('Differentiating between voluntary quit and involuntary disconnect ... deferred to follow-up work'), but there is no bead tracking this debt.

This means 'leave' events in the event store are ambiguous — a timeout-evicted guest and a player who typed 'quit' both produce identical events. Plugins and analytics that consume leave events cannot distinguish these cases.

Suggested fix: Create a follow-up bead to add a Reason field to DisconnectRequest and pass it through. The current PR is internally consistent but the gap should be tracked explicitly.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-17T03:31:47Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-17T03:31:47Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/117"}

{"id":"holomush-0c3r.20","title":"os.Stat on explicit config path reports 'not found' for permission-denied, misleading operators","description":"File: internal/config/config.go, lines 153-158.

When the user passes an explicit --config path:
  if _, err := os.Stat(configPath); err != nil {
      return "", true, oops.Code("CONFIG_NOT_FOUND").
          With("path", configPath).
          Errorf("config file not found: %s", configPath)
  }

os.Stat returns an error for both os.ErrNotExist AND os.ErrPermission. If the file exists but the process lacks read permission, the operator sees "config file not found: /path/to/config.yaml" — which is factually wrong and will send them on a wild-goose chase looking for a missing file.

Fix: check the specific error type:
  if _, err := os.Stat(configPath); err != nil {
      if errors.Is(err, os.ErrNotExist) {
          return "", true, oops.Code("CONFIG_NOT_FOUND").With("path", configPath).Errorf("config file not found: %s", configPath)
      }
      return "", true, oops.Code("CONFIG_ACCESS_FAILED").With("path", configPath).Wrap(err)
  }","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-18T03:51:43Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-18T03:51:43Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/118"}

{"id":"holomush-0c3r.7","title":"CONFIG_LOAD_FAILED and CONFIG_PARSE_FAILED use same code path with different codes","description":"In internal/config/config.go lines 50-54, the same k.Load error produces two different error codes depending on whether the path was explicit or default:

  if explicit {
      return oops.Code("CONFIG_LOAD_FAILED").With("path", path).Wrap(err)
  }
  // Default path exists but is malformed.
  return oops.Code("CONFIG_PARSE_FAILED").With("path", path).Wrap(err)

Both cases represent a parse/load failure on a file that exists. The distinction between explicit and default path is already captured by the 'explicit' boolean in resolveConfigPath — callers checking error codes would need to know both codes mean 'file could not be parsed'. Using a single CONFIG_PARSE_FAILED code (the more precise description) simplifies error handling and the documented error code surface. The 'explicit' distinction is only meaningful for the not-found check (line 85), not for parse failures.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-18T03:50:42Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-18T03:50:42Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/118"}

{"id":"holomush-0c3r.3","title":"config.Load called twice for same file in runCoreWithDeps","description":"In cmd/holomush/core.go, config.Load is called twice for the same config file: once at line 90 to load the 'core' section, and again at line 348 deep inside runCoreWithDeps to load the 'game' section. This means the file is stat'd, opened, and parsed twice per startup.

The game section config (GameConfig.GuestStartLocation) should be loaded alongside the core config in NewCoreCmd's RunE, then passed into runCoreWithDeps. This eliminates the second file parse and makes the config loading boundary consistent — all loading happens at the command boundary, not buried inside the run function.

Suggested fix: add a gameConfig field or separate param to runCoreWithDeps, load both sections in RunE before calling the run function:

  var gameConfig config.GameConfig
  if err := config.Load(configFile, cmd, cfg, "core"); err != nil { return err }
  if err := config.Load(configFile, cmd, &gameConfig, "game"); err != nil { return err }
  return runCoreWithDeps(cmd.Context(), cfg, &gameConfig, cmd, nil)","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-18T03:50:27Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-18T03:50:27Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/118"}

{"id":"holomush-0c3r.15","title":"INVALID_START_LOCATION wraps parseErr without including the bad value string","description":"File: cmd/holomush/core.go, around line 357.

When ulid.Parse fails, the error is returned as:
  return oops.Code("INVALID_START_LOCATION").Wrap(parseErr)

The value being parsed (startLocationStr) is never included in the error context. If an operator sets guest_start_location to a malformed string in config.yaml, the error message will say something like 'ulid: bad data size when unmarshaling' with no indication of which string caused the failure.

Fix: add the bad value as context:
  return oops.Code("INVALID_START_LOCATION").With("value", startLocationStr).Wrap(parseErr)

This is especially important because the value originates from a config file, not a hardcoded constant — operators need to see what they wrote.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-18T03:51:17Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-18T03:51:17Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/118"}

