{"description":"In internal/store/session_store.go, PostgresSessionStore.UpdateGridPresent uses non-standard parameter ordering in the SQL:

  UPDATE sessions SET grid_present = $2, updated_at = NOW() WHERE id = $1

Go args: (id, present) — so $1=id, $2=present. This is functionally correct, but inconsistent with every other method in the file, which uses ascending $N in the order arguments appear in SQL. Here the WHERE clause references $1 but id is the first Go argument, while SET uses $2 but present is the second. While correct today, this is a maintenance hazard: if a future developer reorders Go arguments or the SQL, data could be silently corrupted. Suggested fix: swap Go argument order to (present, id) so SET uses $1 and WHERE uses $2, matching SQL reading order.","issue_type":"task","priority":2}

