{"id":"holomush-mq5o.10","title":"UpdateGridPresent SQL has parameter order mismatch: $1 is id but goes to WHERE, $2 is present but goes to SET","description":"In internal/store/session_store.go, PostgresSessionStore.UpdateGridPresent has a parameter binding mismatch:

  UPDATE sessions SET grid_present = $2, updated_at = NOW() WHERE id = $1

The Go call passes: (id, present) — so $1=id and $2=present, which is correct for this SQL. However, the parameter order in the SQL ($2 before $1) is inconsistent with every other method in the same file (all others use ascending parameter order $1, $2, $3... in the same order as the Go arguments). This is a readability hazard that is one refactor away from becoming a silent data corruption bug if the argument order is ever changed. More critically, if a reviewer compares with the pattern elsewhere and 'fixes' it by reordering SQL to use $1 for grid_present and $2 for id, it would silently corrupt data. This should be made consistent: either change SQL to SET grid_present = $1 WHERE id = $2 and swap the Go args, or keep current binding but reorder args to match ($1=present, $2=id). The safest fix is to use named parameters or restructure to match the project-wide convention of ascending $N matching argument order.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-19T19:13:16Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-19T19:13:16Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/holomush/holomush/pull/123"}
